00:00:34.540 --> 00:00:36.840
needed to find
somebody who could talk

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:39.650
about the future of
technology in a way that

00:00:39.650 --> 00:00:42.940
was optimistic and
exciting and that

00:00:42.940 --> 00:00:46.850
was going to get people to
think about these kind of very

00:00:46.850 --> 00:00:50.490
complicated and sometimes
difficult issues

00:00:50.490 --> 00:00:54.090
with a positive undertone
to what they were saying.

00:00:54.090 --> 00:00:57.420
And we were
absolutely so excited

00:00:57.420 --> 00:00:59.450
when we came across the
work of Jason Silva,

00:00:59.450 --> 00:01:01.590
and a few weeks after
we talked to Jason

00:01:01.590 --> 00:01:03.540
and started to arrange
for him to come,

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:05.390
we found out that he
was speaking at TED.

00:01:05.390 --> 00:01:06.860
And I was fortunate
enough to see

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:08.780
him speak there,
introducing a video

00:01:08.780 --> 00:01:13.760
he had made for that
conference, and I thought, yes,

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:16.790
this is something that's going
to be really wonderful to see

00:01:16.790 --> 00:01:19.040
here in the Festival
of Dangerous Ideas.

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:23.560
Jason is someone who's
hard to categorize.

00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:25.920
He's not someone
where I can say,

00:01:25.920 --> 00:01:28.420
yes, he's the author of
XYZ, and he's a professor

00:01:28.420 --> 00:01:29.400
here and there.

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:33.730
Jason is a philosopher,
a filmmaker, a visionary,

00:01:33.730 --> 00:01:34.360
I think.

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:36.560
Someone who, above all,
is a really extraordinary

00:01:36.560 --> 00:01:41.580
communicator about science,
about complexity, and about

00:01:41.580 --> 00:01:42.540
the future.

00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:45.690
So I'm delighted that he's here
to talk to us this afternoon.

